  "title": "AI in regulated industries: a per-regulation playbook",
  "subtitle": "What HIPAA, GLBA, SOX, GDPR, CCPA, the EU AI Act, NIST AI RMF, and ISO 42001 actually ask of you when AI touches the work",
  "accent": "#22F0D5",
  "intro": "If you work in healthcare, finance, public sector, or any business that handles EU or California personal data, \"we use AI\" is now a regulated act. The frameworks below do not ban AI. They ask you to prove three things: that you knew what data the model touched, that a person remained accountable for consequential outputs, and that you can show your work to an auditor or a regulator who shows up later. This page is the per-regulation playbook we use ourselves when wiring AtomEons tools for partners in regulated lanes.\n\nIt is opinionated about one thing in particular. Consumer AI products are not the same product as their enterprise counterparts. ChatGPT (the consumer app) and the OpenAI API are different surfaces with different contracts. Claude (the consumer app) and the Anthropic API or Enterprise plans are different surfaces. Azure OpenAI Service is again different. The regulation almost always lives in those contracts, not in the model itself. If you take one thing from this page, take that.\n\nThe structure: each framework gets a do, never-do, and evidence row. The evidence row is the artifact an auditor will ask for. We cite the official text where it exists, and we are explicit when something is best-effort as of June 2026 because the landscape moves quickly. The EU AI Act in particular shifted in May 2026 and is still being amended. Check primary sources before you ship.\n\nThis is a starting framework, not legal advice. If your AI deployment touches PHI, regulated financial data, EU residents, or California residents in a significant-decision context, retain counsel licensed in the relevant jurisdiction before launch. The compliance gap is almost never the technology. It is the absence of a written program, a named owner, and a logged decision.",
